## Architecture Contract (Core Artifact)

The **Architecture Contract** defines:
- Invariants that must always hold
- What is forbidden
- What other phases may safely assume

Examples:
- Immutability guarantees
- Ownership rules
- Determinism requirements
- Dependency constraints

Violating a contract is a **system-level error**.

---

## Module Map

The module map defines:
- Module boundaries
- Responsibilities and non-responsibilities
- Allowed dependencies
- Data ownership at a high level

It does NOT define:
- Execution order
- Internal algorithms
- Function-level APIs

---

## Decision Log (ADR)

Every meaningful architectural choice should be logged.

Each ADR records:
- Context
- Options considered
- Decision made
- Rationale
- Consequences

This preserves architectural memory and prevents decision drift.

---

## Architecture Change Classification

All proposed changes after Phase 2 begins must be classified:

### Class A — Feature-Only
- No invariant changes
- No boundary changes

Action:
- Proceed to specs & briefs

---

### Class B — Architectural Extension (Compatible)
- Adds new capabilities
- Preserves existing invariants

Action:
- Update Architecture Contract (additive)
- Update Module Map
- Regenerate affected specs & briefs
- Mandatory targeted audit

---

### Class C — Architectural Mutation (Breaking)
- Changes invariants or assumptions
- Breaks compatibility

Action:
- Explicit architecture revision
- Contract version bump
- Spec regeneration
- Brief regeneration
- Mandatory re-audit

Only the Architect may classify changes.

---

## Versioning Rules (Architecture)

- Exactly one **active** contract and module map
- Active documents have **no version suffix**
- Superseded versions are renamed:
    ARCHITECTURE_CONTRACT_v2.md
    module_map_v2.md
Old versions are never edited.

---

## How Phase 2 Ends (Handoff to Phase 3)

Phase 2 is complete when:
- Architecture Contract is stable
- Module Map is clear
- Major decisions are logged
- No unresolved architectural ambiguity remains

At this point:
- Specs may be authored
- Briefs may be generated
- Implementation may begin

Downstream phases must not reinterpret architecture.

---

## Strict Phase Boundary Rules

Phase 2 must NOT:
- Edit Phase-1 concept documents
- Carry ambiguity forward
- Delegate decisions to implementers
- Treat ideas as requirements

Phase boundaries are explicit and enforced.

---

## One-Line Rule (Memorize This)

**Phase 1 explores intent.  
Phase 2 commits to structure.  
Everything after obeys.**

